Package projects.spatial.knnutils

Interface PriorityQueue<T>

  • All Superinterfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<T>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    BoundedPriorityQueue
    public interface PriorityQueue<T>
extends java.lang.Iterable<T>

    PriorityQueue is an interface specification for Priority Queues. Those are queues which, instead of operating in a FIFO manner, will insert elements according to a provided priority, which is not necessarily an integer and where lower number means better priority.

    Minor detail: since PriorityQueue is an interface, all of its methods are implicitly public, so the explicit scope modifier is not needed in the source.

    YOU SHOULD ***NOT*** EDIT THIS CLASS! If you do, you risk not passing our tests!

    • Method Detail

      • enqueue

        void enqueue​(T element,
             java.math.BigDecimal priority)

        Insert element in the PriorityQueue according to its priority. Lower is better. We allow for non-integer priorities such that the PriorityQueue can be used for orderings where the prioritization is not rounded to integer quantities, such as Euclidean Distances in KNN queries.

        Parameters:
        element - The element to insert in the queue.
        priority - The priority of the element. Encoded as an arbitrary precision BigDecimal.
        See Also:
        KDPoint.distanceSquared(KDPoint), BigDecimal

      • dequeue

        T dequeue()
        Return the minimum priority element in the queue, simultaneously removing it from the structure.
        Returns:
        The minimum priority element in the queue, or null if the queue is empty.

      • first

        T first()
        Return, but don't remove, the minimum priority element from the queue.
        Returns:

      • size

        int size()
        Query the queue about its size. Empty queues have a size of 0.
        Returns:
        The size of the queue. Returns 0 if the queue is empty.

      • isEmpty

        boolean isEmpty()
        Query the queue about emptiness. A queue is empty iff it contains 0 (zero) elements.
        Returns:
        true iff the queue contains 0 (zero) elements.
